GIT PRACTICAL NOTES

COMMITTING CHANGES
- git commit -m "message" is used to save changes to the local repository.
- Example: git commit -m "Add hello and test files"
- Output shows which files were added or changed.

VIEWING COMMIT HISTORY
- git log shows the commit history in the current branch.
- Example output shows commit hash, author, date, and message.
- HEAD -> main indicates the current branch and latest commit.

CHECKING OUT COMMITS
- git checkout <commit-hash> lets you view a previous commit.
- This puts you in a detached HEAD state:
  - You can explore, make experimental changes, or commit.
  - Changes made here do not affect main unless you create a new branch.

RETURNING TO A BRANCH
- git checkout main returns you to the main branch.
- git checkout -f main forces a switch to main (useful if conflicts exist).

PULLING CHANGES
- git pull fetches and merges changes from the remote repository.
- If the branch has no tracking information, Git will ask you to specify the remote and branch.
- Example: git branch --set-upstream-to=<remote>/<branch> main

COMMON ERRORS
- Typing 'branch' alone will not work in PowerShell; use git branch to list branches.
- Detached HEAD state is normal when checking out a specific commit; create a branch to save work if needed.

ADVANCED CONCEPTS TO LEARN
- Merge Conflicts: When Git cannot automatically merge changes from different branches.
- Reset: Undo commits locally.
- Revert: Undo a commit safely by creating a new commit.
- Stash: Temporarily save changes without committing.
- Cherry-pick: Apply a specific commit from one branch to another.

FINAL NOTES
- Always commit your changes before switching branches.
- Use git log to track history and understand what has been committed.
- Learn to handle conflicts, reset, revert, stash, and cherry-pick to manage changes effectively.
